Buisness Background/Motivation¶

The business problem is to predict whether customers have health insurance, which can guide marketing efforts, customer outreach, and tailored policy offerings. By using data science, we want to build a model that predicts insurance status using customer data. The main business question is: ​ "Which customers might not have health insurance, and how can we predict and target them for insurance enrollment?"​

The dataset includes US customers demographic, socioeconomic, and housing-related features like age, gender, income, and housing type.

The main contributions of this work are the deep understanding of the data and the creation of a machine learning model to help the company to achieve more clients, targeting the correct people. The idea is that the company could feed some client's data to the model and it would predict if they already have health insurance or not.

Dropping and One-hot encoding¶

Here we drop the uncessary columns, like the id column and code_column which represents the state. We also create a function to encode the categorial data.

In [34]:
# Drop unnamed
df = df.drop(columns=['Unnamed: 0'])

# Drop custid and code_column
df = df.drop(columns=['custid', 'code_column'])
# code_column corresponds to state

df['is_employed'] = df['is_employed'].map({False: "unemployed", True: "employed"})
df['is_employed'] = df['is_employed'].fillna("not_in_workforce")

df['num_vehicles'] = df['num_vehicles'].astype(int)

df['gas_usage'] = df['gas_usage'].astype(int)
df['gas_usage'] = df['gas_usage'].replace([1, 2, 3], 0)
In [35]:
def encoding(df):
    df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['sex'], drop_first=True)

    df['recent_move_b'] = df['recent_move_b'].map({'F': 0, 'T': 1})

    # One-hot encoding
    df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['marital_status'], drop_first=True)
    df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['housing_type'], drop_first=True)
    df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['state_of_res'], drop_first=True)
    df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['is_employed'], drop_first=True)

    df = df.replace({True: 1, False: 0}).infer_objects(copy=False)
    
    return df

Data transformation¶

As it was seen, income and gas_usage are highly skewed and age has some unusual values that need to be handled. Therefore, we apply a logarithmic transformation to the first two and remove the outliers from the first one, since they're most likely wrong values.

In [37]:

# Handling outliers for income, age, and gas usage
df['income'] = df['income'].apply(
    lambda x: np.log(x) if x > 0 else (-np.log(abs(x)) if x < 0 else 0)
)
#df['income'] = df['income'].where(df['income'] <= 0.1 * 10**6, 0.1 * 10**6)
df = df[(df['age'] != 0) & (df['age'] <= 110)]
df['gas_usage'] = df['gas_usage'].apply(lambda x: np.log(x) if x > 0 else 0)

Data scaling¶

For some models we will apply scaling, whenever it is required in order to obtain better results. So we create this function:

In [40]:
from sklearn import preprocessing

def scaling(df):
    scaler = preprocessing.StandardScaler()

    # Identificar colunas binárias (valores únicos {0, 1})
    no_change = [col for col in df.columns if set(df[col].unique()) == {0, 1} or col == 'custid' or col == 'health_ins'] #Por causa do teste depois
    continuous_cols = [col for col in df.columns if col not in no_change]

    # Escalar apenas as colunas contínuas
    df_scaled = df.copy()
    df_scaled[continuous_cols] = scaler.fit_transform(df[continuous_cols])
    
    # Colunas binárias permanecem inalteradas
    return df_scaled

Modeling¶

In the modeling phase, we will compare 7 different models:

  • Nearest neighbor
  • Bayesian Classifier
  • Decision Trees
  • Tree ensembles (Random Forest and XGBoost)
  • Support Vector Machines
  • Neural Network Classifier

Since the dataset is highly unbalanced, we will compare the non-balanced and balanced dataset for each model. For balancing, we will use SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique), which is a technique that genarates synthetic samples for the minority class.

For the models which have hyper-paremeters that can be tuned, which is almost always the case, we tune them by using cross-validation.

In order to obtain more reliable results, we create train-test splits of 0.8/0.2 for each model and peform cross-validation only in the training set for hyper-parameter tuning, so that the model is evaluated with data it has never "seen".

Note:¶

Although we print all the metrics, for model comparison we will use F1 score, recall and AUC, since they are the metrics that best align with our buisness goal. Our goal is to predict who does not have insurance in order to target them in marketing efforts.

Why Recall instead of Precision:

A false negative would occur if the model predicts that a customer has health insurance when they actually do not. In this case, the customer would be missed for outreach efforts, and they wouldn’t be targeted for potential insurance enrollment. If a false positive happened, this would result at most in unnecessary marketing efforts, which aren't as costly as missing clients.

Why F1 and AUC:

They penalize false positives and false negatives more fairly. In addition, F1 is the metric used in the Kaggle competition.

First we create a evaluation function to use for each model:

In [41]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, roc_auc_score, roc_curve, classification_report
import pickle

def evaluation(y,y_pred):
    # Scores
    print("classification report: \n", classification_report(y,y_pred))
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 6)) 
    # Confusion Matrix
    sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(y, y_pred), 
            annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", cbar=False, square=True, ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title("Confusion Matrix")
    axes[0].set_xlabel("Predicted")
    axes[0].set_ylabel("Actual")

    # ROC Curve
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y, y_pred)
    auc_score = roc_auc_score(y, y_pred)

    axes[1].plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"ROC Curve (AUC = {auc_score:.4f})", color="blue")
    axes[1].plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle="--", color="gray", label="Random Guessing")
    axes[1].set_title("Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve")
    axes[1].set_xlabel("False Positive Rate (FPR)")
    axes[1].set_ylabel("True Positive Rate (TPR)")
    axes[1].legend(loc="lower right")
    axes[1].grid()

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Then, we define the SMOTE object to be used for the balanced predictions:

from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

Finally, we create a scorer to use on cross-validation for hyperparameter tuning. We use the F1 score since it's a balanced precision/recall criteria and the evaluation metric used on the Kaggle competition. Since we want to predict the clients without health-insurance, we consider 0 as the reference.

K-NN¶

We start by scaling the data with the scaling function to standardize the preprocessed dataset "dfc" and store it in "dfknn". The next step it to separate features (X) and target (y), where y is the target variable (health_ins, which we want to predict), and X contains the feature variables (everything except health_ins).

Unbalanced:

Here, we create the train_test_split with stratification. The stratification is made to ensure that the class proportions in the training and testing datasets are the same as in the original dataset, to avoid one class being underrepresented in the split. Shuffling is also done by default, which also helps in creating reliable results.

In [39]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42)

Then we use hyperparameter tuning with Grid Search, and fit the grid search to the training data. After fitting, grid_search.best_estimator_.predict() retrieves the best value for n_neighbors (this is the k that performed best during cross-validation), refits the entire train data, and computes the final prediction on the test data with the refitted model. We also apply stratification for the k-folds used in cross-validation, which will be repeated for all models with cross-validation.

Decision Trees¶

For the decision tree models, although technically it could work without encoding, the sklearn model require numerical columns, so we used the encoded dataframe. In addition, we originally did not apply the scaling function, since these type of models do not require it, but in order to use the ensemble model we had to scale so that we could be consistent with the other scaled models used. We also found out that scaling actually improved the recall, which was not expected, but could be due to bias mitigation, since it allows splits to focus on genuinely relevant features.

In order to find the ideal value for the tree depth, we placed side by side a plot showing the F1 score for different depth values and the learning curve to check the model's performance and see if there is any underfitting or overfitting.

axs[1].fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std, train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color='blue')

Ensemble Regression¶

Here we do an Ensemble Regression to aggregate the predictions of several models.

In [46]:
from sklearn.ensemble import StackingClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

Then we load a list of pre-trained models from files stored on disk: for each file in the list, it opens the file in binary read mode ("rb"). It deserializes the model using the pickle.load() function. The deserialized model is appended to a list called models. The function returns the list of models.

In [47]:
def load_models(model_files):
    models = []
    for file in model_files:
        with open(file, "rb") as f:
            models.append(pickle.load(f))  
    return models

Implementing stacked ensemble learning for unbalanced data:

First of all we load pre-trained models (each file contains a serialized model trained on unbalanced data).

In [52]:
unbalanced_models = load_models([
    "unbalanced_bayesian.pkl",
    "unbalanced_dt.pkl",
    "unbalanced_knn.pkl",
    "unbalanced_rf.pkl",
    "unbalanced_svm.pkl",
    "unbalanced_xg.pkl",
    "unbalanced_nn.pkl"
])

Then, we create the Base Learners (a list of tuples, where each tuple consists of a string representing the model's name (e.g., 'bayesian') and the corresponding pre-trained model from unbalanced_models).

In [62]:
base_learners = [
    ('bayesian', unbalanced_models[0]),   
    ('dt', unbalanced_models[1]),       
    ('knn', unbalanced_models[2]),      
    ('rf', unbalanced_models[3]),        
    ('svm', unbalanced_models[4]),       
    ('xg', unbalanced_models[5]),        
    ('nn', unbalanced_models[6])          
]

Then, we define the meta-learner: the final estimator that combines the predictions of the base learners. The next step is to create the stacking ensemble, that uses predictions from the base learners as features to train the meta-learner. Then we train the stacking model and make predictions.

In [ ]:
meta_learner = LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced', random_state=42)


stacking_model = StackingClassifier(estimators=base_learners, final_estimator=meta_learner)


stacking_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
ensemble_preds_stacking = stacking_model.predict(X_test)

Results¶

Here we aggregate the results for each model used, both in the balanced and the unbalanced datasets:

There are 3 tables: the first has results for the balanced dataset,the second for the unbalanced dataset and the lats one with results of the "best" ensemble, which was the ensemble created by combining both balanced and unbalanced models. For each one we have the results for both class 0 and 1, being class 0 the one we are more interested in.

Now focusing only on the class 0, by using the darker green color we highlight the best results in each table for the metrics we are interested in, namely F1-Score, AUC and Recall. Similarly, in light green we highlight the best least important metrics in each table. When there is a tie, all of the highest peforming metrics are highlighted.

Conclusions:¶

  • Balanced:

    • F1:

      For F1, the best models were Random Forest, Neural Networks and the Ensemble, with a F1-Score of 0.32. This score is usually considered low, which means we could not achieve models which are great at balancing precision and recall. So although the recall is fairly good in those models, the precision is poor, which brings the F1 value down. However, comparing with the baseline model, these models more than doubled the F1, which represent a 113% increase.

    • Recall:

      The best recall was obtained by Bayesian Classifier (0.78), which is unexpected given its simplicity. However, other models also achieved similar values. A value of 0.78 is considered good and shows our model is only is missing 22% of the actual positives, which means clients without insurance won't be greatly missed. The baseline had a recall of 0.48, so we improved it in 62.5%.

    • AUC:

      Regarding AUC, the best models were the Neural Networks and the Ensemble, both with 0.73. This means the model has a 73% probability of correctly ranking a randomly chosen positive instance higher than a randomly chosen negative instance, that is, it is good at distinguishing between classes.

    • Precision and Accuracy:

      For both of these metrics, the Random Forest peformed the best. If we wanted to compare using F1 as the primary metric and precision and accuracy as tiebraker criteria, we could say the Random Forest model was the best model overall for the balanced dataset.

  • Unbalanced:

    • F1:

      For F1, the best models were Random Forest and XGBoost, with a F1-Score of 0.33. It's a very close to score to what was obtained in the balanced case, which means balancing didn't represent a great advantage overall for this metric.

    • Recall:

      The best recall was obtained by the Ensemble (0.78), the same high score obtained in the balanced case. The conclusions remain the same as for the balanced, but this time for the ensemble model.

    • AUC:

      Regarding AUC, the best models were the Neural Networks and the Ensemble, both with 0.74. Just 0.01 higher than the balanced version, again there is no big difference.

    • Precision and Accuracy:

      For both of these metrics, the Neutal Networks peformed the best. Since it does not have the best recall or F1, we cannot do much with this information.

  • Best Ensemble:

    • F1:

      Was the same as on the unbalanced case, so no improvment.

    • Recall:

      It was the best overall (0.79), but for a slow margin (0.01).

    • AUC:

      It tied with the unbalanced case, with 0.74, which is a good value, as mentioned.

NOTE: Gven we tuned the hyperparameters using a F1 scorer, we obtained the best models for that metric. For that reason, it's possible the recall values could be higher if we tuned using a recall scorer. The same is also valid for the other metrics.

df_masked = pd.read_csv('customer_test_masked.csv')

#df_masked.isna().sum()

# 1. Impute values for "housing_type" (categorical) using the mode
df_masked["housing_type"] = df_masked["housing_type"].fillna(df_masked["housing_type"].mode()[0])

# 2. Impute values for "num_vehicles" (integer numeric) using the median
df_masked["num_vehicles"] = df_masked["num_vehicles"].fillna(df_masked["num_vehicles"].median())

# 3. Impute values for "recent_move_b" (boolean) using the mode
df_masked["recent_move_b"] = df_masked["recent_move_b"].fillna(df_masked["recent_move_b"].mode()[0])

# 4. Impute values for "gas_usage" (integer numeric) using the median
df_masked["gas_usage"] = df_masked["gas_usage"].fillna(df_masked["gas_usage"].median())

# Drop unnamed
df_masked = df_masked.drop(columns=['Unnamed: 0'])
#df_masked = df_masked.drop(columns=['custid'])
df_masked = df_masked.drop(columns=['code_column'])
# code_column corresponds to state


df_masked['is_employed'] = df_masked['is_employed'].map({False: "unemployed", True: "employed"})
df_masked['is_employed'] = df_masked['is_employed'].fillna("not_in_workforce")

df_masked['num_vehicles'] = df_masked['num_vehicles'].astype(int)

df_masked['gas_usage'] = df_masked['gas_usage'].astype(int)
df_masked['gas_usage'] = df_masked['gas_usage'].replace([1, 2, 3], 0)


df_masked= encoding(df_masked)


# Handling outliers for income, age, and gas usage
